The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | In the City
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                      IN THE CITY
                  
	 City-based former international umpires Subrata Banerjee and Subrata Porel recently cleared the BCCIs course for Umpires Educators (also known as Umpires Coaches) held in Mumbai. The course was conducted by Australian umpire Simon Taufel. Both Banerjee and Porel are now eligible to join the faculty at the newly-inaugurated BCCIs Umpires Academy in Nagpur. Also, seven umpires  Sabyasachi Sarkar, Abhijit Bhattacharya, Mukesh Sinha, Indranil Chakrabarty, Manish Saha, Atanu Sarkar and Sanjib Pandey  who cleared the BCCIs LevelI course last year will undergo a refresher course at the Umpires Academy in June.          
	 West Bengal Police coach Arun Sarkar has filed a lawsuit against the Cricket Association of Bengal challenging the decision of their tournament committee to cancel the result of Polices match against Aryan when the former chased a record target of 515. It was found out that there was an error in calculation in the West Bengal Police scoresheet. A case has been filed against CAB in the Alipore court by Police coach Arun Sarkar, joint secretary Arun Mitra confirmed.          
	 Tapan Memorial beat Netaji Subhas Institute by two wickets in a CAB league championship play-off match on Sunday. Chasing a mammoth target of 501, Anup Barik scored 111 as Tapan Memorial scored 507/8 (11 penalty runs) to win the match.      
	Summarised scores      
	Tollygunge Agragami 150 in 52.5 overs (D. Chowdhury 5/55). ABP Sports Club 155/4 in 29.3 overs(D. Singh 49 n.o.). ABP won by 6 wkts.      
	 East Bengal 423/9 (P.S. Bhattacharjee 166, D. Dasgupta 64). Taltala Institute 158 (P. Mukharjee 4/56, S.S. Singh 3/39). East Bengal won by 265 runs.      
	 Netaji Subhas Institute 500/8 (M. Adak 103, M. Chakrabarty 181). Tapan Memorial 507/8 (A. Barik 111). Tapan Memorial won by 2 wickets.      
	 Shambazar 314 (S. Das 314, S. Das 71). Bhawanipore 250 (A.S. Mukharjee 59). Shambazar won by 64 runs.          
	 Souvik Chowdhury won the boys singles title while Urmimala Sengupta was the champion among the girls at the All Bengal 47th Hooghly District Table Tennis Championship. Souvik also won the mens singles title. Tania Mondal won the womens singles trophy.                                                                                                                                                      
